GIANAtree

Making tree plot from isometric embedding matrix

GIANA provides -M option to output the isometric embedding matrix for each CDR3. Users can combine the numeric coordinates with the TCR clustering information to visualize the relationships between different TCR clusters. Here we use neighbor joining tree as an illustration:

We begin with loading the data and required packages:

library(ape)  ## generate neighbor joining tree
## Warning: package 'ape' was built under R version 3.5.2
ffc='TCRantigen--RotationEncodingBL62.txt'  ## GIANA standard output
ffm='TCRantigen--RotationEncodingBL62.txt_EncodingMatrix.txt'  ## Output matrix with -M option

d1=read.table(ffc, header=F,sep='\t',stringsAsFactors = F)
Mat=read.table(ffm, header=F,sep='\t',stringsAsFactors = F)

## combining antigen annotation
tmp=strsplit(d1[,6],'_')
tmp=unlist(sapply(tmp,function(x)x[length(x)]))
d1=cbind(d1,Ag=tmp)
d1[grep('Antigen:M1',d1[,7]),7]='GILGFVFTL'
d1[grep('Antigen:pp65',d1[,7]),7]='NLVPMVATV'
d1[grep('Antigen:BMLF',d1[,7]),7]='GLCTLVAML'
d1[grep('Antigen:CMV-NLV',d1[,7]),7]='NLVPMVATV'
d1[grep('Antigen:CMV-MLN',d1[,7]),7]='MLNIPSINV'
d1[grep('Antigen:YFV-LLW',d1[,7]),7]='LLWNGPMAV'
d1[which(d1[,7]=='LLW'),7]='LLWNGPMAV'
d1[grep('Antigen:HCV-KLV',d1[,7]),7]="KLVALGINAV"

Next, we match the embedding matrix with each CDR3 sequences. Note: generation of the matrix only relies on the amino acid of the CDR3s.

Mat=Mat[,c(1,6:101)]
Mat=unique(Mat)
rownames(Mat)=Mat[,1]
Mat=Mat[,2:97]

## now combine TCR clusters with isometric coordinates
d1=cbind(d1, Mat[d1[,1],])

Althought GIANA is able to handle millions of TCRs, it is usually not feasible to visualize all the data. A practical solution is to select the clusters of interest, and visualize a smaller subset.

## Choose a subset of TCRs specific to the M1 GIL epitope
tt0=table(d1[,2], d1[,7])
LL=apply(tt0,1,function(x)length(which(x>0)))
names(which(LL==1))-> vv.tcrG
nn.pure=rownames(tt0[vv.tcrG,])
vv.select=grep('GIL',d1[,6])

nna=unique(d1[vv.select,2])
nna=intersect(nna,nn.pure)
## nna contains too many clusters. Randomly select 20 of them.
nna1=sample(nna, 20)
ddc.s=d1[which(d1[,2] %in% nna1),]

From coordinates, we can derive a pairwise distance matrix using Pearsons correltion r: Distance = sqrt(1-r)

Mat.cor=cor(t(ddc.s[, 8:103]))
Mat.dist=sqrt(1-Mat.cor)

To make a plot that reflects the relationships of the clusters and their antigen-specificities:

tr = nj(Mat.dist)

tr$tip.label = gsub('\\.[1-9]{1}$','', tr$tip.label)

## A list of high-contrast colors
COLs= c("dodgerblue2","gold", # red
        "green4",
        "#6A3D9A", # purple
        "#FF7F00", # orange
        "cyan",
        "skyblue2","#FB9A99", # lt pink
        "palegreen2",
        "#CAB2D6", # lt purple
        "#FDBF6F", # lt orange
        "gray70", "khaki2",
        "maroon","orchid1","deeppink1","blue1","steelblue4",
        "darkturquoise","green1","yellow4","yellow3",
        "darkorange4","brown")

col.gr=COLs[1:20]
names(col.gr)=nna1
par(mar=c(0,0,0,0))
plot.phylo(tr, font=2, cex=0.9, 
           tip.color=col.gr[as.character(ddc.s[,2])], ## color the CDR3s according to antigen-specificity
           align.tip.label=TRUE, x.lim=c(0,1.1))
